msgid "Tena kho pana samayena aññataro bhikkhu gāmakaṃ gacchanto aññataraṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca—"
msgstr "On one occasion, as he was going to the village, a monk said to another monk,"

#. <span class="note" hidden><i lang="pli">Āvuso tuyhaṃ upaṭṭhākakulaṃ vutto vajjemīti</i>. The unusual expression <i lang="pli">vutto vajjemi</i> recurs in the next two cases. <i lang="pli">Vajjemi</i> is apparently an optative formation from <i lang="pli">vadāmi</i>, “I could say,” whereas <i lang="pli">vutto</i> seems to be the past participle of <i lang="pli">vuccati</i>, “spoken to,” the overall meaning being, “I, (having been) spoken to, could say to the family that supports you.” The idea conveyed seems to be the taking of a message, and this is reinforced by the commentary: <i lang="pli">Tava vacanena vadāmīti attho</i>, “The meaning is, ‘I will speak your statement.’”</span> 
msgctxt "pli-tv-bu-vb-pj2:148.2"
msgid "“āvuso, tuyhaṃ upaṭṭhākakulaṃ vutto vajjemī”ti."
msgstr "“I can take a message to the family that supports you.”"

